fisheries impacts on economies and oceans from invisible workforce the leopold leadership program skip to main content search this site the leopold leadership program about fellows news fellowship information resources fellows login home 2013 fellowship information all cohort reunion june 19 21 2012 in this section 2012 newsletters newsletter archive fisheries impacts on economies and oceans from invisible workforce rashid sumaila published on january 31 2012 photo mumbo jiggy sumaila the number of people worldwide whose livelihoods depend on marine fisheries is 260 million a figure 1.75 times larger than previously thought according to new research by rashid sumaila 2009 and a colleague their study which covered 144 coastal countries included many small scale fishing operations that had not been counted before among them unlicensed fishers the revised figure suggests larger impacts on fish stocks from fishing and possibly on the world's economies if fish stocks crash the authors say tags fisheries economics fisheries management 2012 leopold leadership program the stanford woods institute for the environment stanford university stanford ca 94305
